          {
            "id": "0da79675-66f1-46e2-936f-8035e9f1c6d6",
            "url": "http://res.cloudinary.com/dozsqvbas/image/upload/v1772397447/AvIDfx/rjjjgnvnwfzqx2m5in6s.webp",
            "width": 2500,
            "height": 1875,
            "credit": "",
            "caption": "<p>Warm weather and sun over the past week have fueled the rapid settlement of the mid-February snowfall. Water has already moved through most of the snowpack on south, east, and west slopes, decreasing the chance of wet avalanches and strengthening the snowpack with recent cooler temperatures. You can track the progress of meltwater by identifying percolation tubes like these ones pictured. As warm temperatures return we do not anticipate wet avalanches, but we do anticipate poor mushy snow and recommend moving off slopes with moist trap door conditions.</p>",
            "tag": "avalanche",
            "altText": "A crystal card sits behind narrow percolation tubes in a snowpack",
            "dateTaken": "2026-02-28T20:26:48Z",
            "isArchived": false
